

Accepted


{{ project_name }} requires a clear separation of concerns to enable
independent testing, flexible infrastructure swapping, and long-term
maintainability. The team evaluated layered, hexagonal (ports & adapters),
and clean architecture patterns.


Adopt **clean / hexagonal architecture** (ports & adapters) with the following
layer structure that maps directly to the project source tree:

- **core/** — Pure domain: entities, value objects, domain events, enums,
  exception hierarchy, interface protocols (ports). ZERO external dependencies.
- **application/** — Use cases, application services, DTOs, command/query
  handlers, mappers. Imports from `core` only.
- **ports/** — Driving adapters: API routes (FastAPI), CLI commands (Typer),
  web controllers, API schemas, DI container. Framework imports allowed here.
- **adapters/** — Driven adapters: persistence (SQLAlchemy repositories),
  cache, messaging, email, storage, auth (JWT). Implements core protocols.
- **infrastructure/** — Low-level technical primitives: DB engines, HTTP
  clients, security hashing, scheduling.
- **config/** — Separate pillar: pydantic-settings, logging, constants.
- **utils/** — Shared leaf: stdlib + third-party only, no first-party imports.

### Dependency Rule (Clean Architecture)

Dependencies **always** point inward:

```text
adapters → ports → application → core
              ↑
        infrastructure
```

- Core **never** imports from outer layers.
- Application services depend on **core protocols**, never on concrete
  adapter classes (Dependency Inversion Principle).
- The Unit of Work protocol exposes typed repository properties so that
  services access persistence through the UoW without importing adapters.

### Frontend Separation (when applicable)

```text
api/       → Backend HTTP communication (fetch wrappers)
models/    → Zod schemas + TypeScript types (shared contracts)
features/  → Feature modules (components, hooks, stores per feature)
hooks/     → Shared React hooks / Lit reactive controllers
stores/    → Global state management
lib/       → Pure utility functions (no side effects)
config/    → Runtime environment configuration
```



- Infrastructure can be swapped without changing business logic
- Domain logic is independently testable with zero framework imports
- Clear dependency boundaries prevent accidental coupling
- The Dependency Rule is enforced by linting (ruff import checks) and
  validated by the Architect agent during PR planning


- More boilerplate for simple CRUD operations
